\begin_layout Standard
It is very convenient to handle all these constructs by their indices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A scalar is denoted as is,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A vector is denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{a}$
\end_inset

,
 where leaving 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 undefined,
 means any index 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathbb{N}_{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A matrix is denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{ab}$
\end_inset

,
 similarly with a vector,
 but now we have two abstract indices 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathbb{N}_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in\mathbb{N}_{m}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
More generally a tensor is denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{a_{1}a_{2}\ldots a_{\text{rank}x}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Every tensor can be serialized into a vector.
 Lets examing an 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times m$
\end_inset

 matrix example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{multline*}
\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
x_{11} & x_{12} & \cdots & x_{1m}\\
x_{21} & x_{22} & \cdots & x_{2m}\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
x_{n1} & x_{n2} & \cdots & x_{nm}
\end{array}\right]\longrightarrow\\
\longrightarrow[\begin{array}{ccccccccccccc}
x_{11} & x_{12} & \cdots & x_{1m} & x_{21} & x_{22} & \cdots & x_{2m} & \cdots & x_{n1} & x_{n2} & \cdots & x_{nm}\end{array}]=\\
=[\begin{array}{ccccccccccccc}
x_{1} & x_{2} & \cdots & x_{m} & x_{m+1} & x_{m+2} & \cdots & x_{2m} & \cdots & x_{(n-1)\cdot m+1} & x_{(n-1)\cdot m+2} & \cdots & x_{n\cdot m}\end{array}]
\end{multline*}

\end_inset

or in index notation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{ab}\longmapsto x_{(a-1)\cdot m+b}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

