\begin_layout Subsection
Scalars
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Scalars have two operations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
addition 
\begin_inset Formula $+:\mathbb{R}\times\mathbb{R}\longrightarrow\mathbb{R}:x,y\longmapsto x+y$
\end_inset

 with an inverse (subtraction)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
multiplication 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdot:\mathbb{R}\times\mathbb{R}\longrightarrow\mathbb{R}:x,y\longmapsto xy$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Vectors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Vectors have addition defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x+y=[\begin{array}{cccc}
x_{1}+y_{1} & x_{2}+y_{2} & \cdots & x_{n}+y_{n}\end{array}]=x_{a}+y_{a}
\]

\end_inset

which is well defined because 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{a}$
\end_inset

 are scalars 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall a$
\end_inset

,
 and addition is defined for scalars.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 must have the same dimension!
 We can also substract two vectors.
 The zero vector is thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=[\begin{array}{cccc}
0 & 0 & \cdots & 0\end{array}]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Vectors have multiplication with a scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda x=[\begin{array}{cccc}
\lambda x_{1} & \lambda x_{2} & \cdots & \lambda x_{n}\end{array}]=\lambda x_{a}
\]

\end_inset

which is well defined because 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{a}$
\end_inset

 is a scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall a$
\end_inset

,
 and multiplication is defined for scalars.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Vectors have an dot product defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\cdot y=x_{1}y_{1}+x_{2}y_{2}+\ldots+x_{n}y_{n}=\sum\nolimits_{a=1}^{n}x_{a}y_{a}
\]

\end_inset

which is well defined because 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{a}$
\end_inset

 are scalars 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall a$
\end_inset

,
 and both addition and multiplication is defined for scalars.
 This is the most basic form of contraction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\cdot y=0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $y=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $x\bot y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This defines a notion of norm for a vector
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Vert x\Vert=\sqrt{x\cdot x}=\sqrt{\vert x_{1}\vert^{2}+\vert x_{2}\vert^{2}+\ldots+\vert x_{n}\vert^{2}}=\sqrt{\sum\nolimits_{a=1}^{n}x_{a}x_{a}}=\sqrt{\sum\nolimits_{a=1}^{n}\vert x_{a}\vert^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Vert x\Vert=0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Matrices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Addition and multiplication with a scalar is similarly defined.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Matrices differ from vectors in that they have their own product!
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times k$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k\times m$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{cc}
 & \left[\begin{array}{cccc}
y_{11} & y_{12} & \cdots & y_{1m}\\
y_{21} & y_{22} & \cdots & y_{2m}\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
y_{k1} & y_{k2} & \cdots & y_{km}
\end{array}\right]\\
\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
x_{11} & x_{12} & \cdots & x_{1k}\\
x_{21} & x_{22} & \cdots & x_{2k}\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
x_{n1} & x_{n2} & \cdots & x_{nk}
\end{array}\right] & \left[\begin{array}{cccc}
z_{11} & z_{12} & \cdots & z_{1m}\\
z_{21} & z_{22} & \cdots & z_{2m}\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
z_{n1} & z_{n2} & \cdots & z_{nm}
\end{array}\right]
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset

or
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
z_{ab}=\sum\nolimits_{c=1}^{k}x_{ac}y_{cb}=x_{a\_}\cdot y_{\_b}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Square matrices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There exists a special kind of matrices,
 the square matrices,
 which are of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 They are special because,
 the matrix product is not only valid for them,
 but it can be stacked too.
 For example,
 for any matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 of the same size 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

,
 the product 
\begin_inset Formula $xyz$
\end_inset

 is defined and also of size 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Careful though!
 The matrix product is not commutative!
 
\begin_inset Formula $xy\ne yx$
\end_inset

 generally.
 Also,
 a unit element makes sense with such a product on square matrices:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I=\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
1 & 0 & \cdots & 0\\
0 & 1 & \cdots & 0\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
0 & 0 & \cdots & 1
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Square matrices have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
a trace:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{tr}x=x_{11}+x_{22}+\ldots+x_{nn}=\sum\nolimits_{a=1}^{n}x_{aa}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
a determinant:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det x=\ldots
\]

\end_inset

For example for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det x=x_{11}x_{22}-x_{12}x_{21}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because square matrices have both addition and a product,
 polynomials are defined on matrix spaces.
 For example
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\exp x=\sum\nolimits_{k=0}^{\infty}\dfrac{x^{n}}{n!}
\]

\end_inset

makes sence for both 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 scalar and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 matrix,
 giving a definition of the exponential mapping on matrices.
 An interesting property is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det(\exp x)=\exp(\text{tr}x)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The transpose of a matrix the one that has as rows the columns of the other:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
x_{11} & x_{12} & \cdots & x_{1m}\\
x_{21} & x_{22} & \cdots & x_{2m}\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
x_{n1} & x_{n2} & \cdots & x_{nm}
\end{array}\right]^{\top}=\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
x_{11} & x_{21} & \cdots & x_{n1}\\
x_{12} & x_{22} & \cdots & x_{n2}\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
x_{1m} & x_{2m} & \cdots & x_{mn}
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a square matrix,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\top}$
\end_inset

has the same size.
 Also 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{tr}x^{\top}=\text{tr}x$
\end_inset

.
 Note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{ab}^{\top}=x_{ba}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Is there a dot product for (square) matrices?
 Yes!
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum\nolimits_{b=1}^{n}\sum\nolimits_{a=1}^{n}x_{ab}y_{ab}=\sum\nolimits_{b=1}^{n}\Big(\sum\nolimits_{a=1}^{n}x_{ba}^{\top}y_{ab}\Big)=\sum\nolimits_{b=1}^{n}(x^{\top}y)_{bb}=\text{tr}(x^{\top}y)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

